SIMPLE: liege
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Liege
<hw>Liege</hw> <pr>(l⟦emac⟧j)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>lige</ets>, <ets>lege</ets>, F. <ets>lige</ets>, LL.
<ets>ligius</ets>, <ets>legius</ets>, liege, unlimited, complete, prob.
of German origin; cf. G. <ets>ledig</ets> free from bonds and obstacles,
MHG. <ets>ledec</ets>, <ets>ledic</ets>, <ets>lidic</ets>, freed,
loosed, and Charta Ottonis de Benthem, ann. 1253, ⟦ldquo⟧<ets>ligius
homo</ets> quod Teutonic⟦egrave⟧ dicitur <ets>ledigman</ets>,⟦rdquo⟧ i.
e., uni soli homagio obligatus, free from all obligations to others;
influenced by L. <ets>ligare</ets> to bind. G. <ets>ledig</ets> perh.
orig. meant, free to go where one pleases, and is perh. akin to E.
<ets>lead</ets> to conduct. Cf. <er>Lead</er> to guide.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Sovereign; independent; having authority or right to
allegiance; <as>as, a <ex>liege</ex> lord</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She looked as grand as doomsday and as grave;⟦br⟧
And he, he reverenced his <qex>liege</qex> lady there.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>serving an independent sovereign or master; bound by
a feudal tenure; obliged to be faithful and loyal to a superior, as a
vassal to his lord; faithful; loyal; <as>as, a <ex>liege</ex> man; a
<ex>liege</ex> subject.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Old Law)</fld> <def>Full; perfect; complete;
pure.</def> <au>Burrill.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Liege homage</b></col> <fld>(Feudal Custom)</fld>,
<cd>that homage of one sovereign or prince to another which acknowledged
an obligation of fealty and services.</cd> -- <col><b>Liege
poustie</b></col> <ety>[L. <ets>legitima potestas</ets>]</ety>
<fld>(Scots Law)</fld>, <cd>perfect, <it>i. e.</it>, legal, power;
specif., having health requisite to do legal acts.</cd> -- <col><b>Liege
widowhood</b></col>, <cd>perfect, <it>i. e.</it>, pure, widowhood.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Liege</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Liege
<hw>Liege</hw> <pr>(l⟦emac⟧j)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
free and independent person; specif., a lord paramount; a
sovereign.</def> <au>Mrs. Browning.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The anointed sovereign of sighs and groans,⟦br⟧
<qex>Liege</qex> of all loiterers and malcontents.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The subject of a sovereign or lord; a
liegeman.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A liege lord seems to have been a lord of a free band; and his
<qex>lieges</qex>, though serving under him, were privileged men, free
from all other obligations, their name being due to their freedom, not
to their service.</q> <rj><qau>Skeat.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Liegeman</ent>⟦br⟧
